			<h2>Soil Recommendation:</h2>
			<p class="descriptions">
				The soil of philodendrons in their natural, tropical habitat is very loose, composed mostly of debris such as leaf litter, wood, and compost. Some don&apos;t even grow in soil at all and grow attached to a tree. As such, the soil used for growing philodendrons indoors should be fast draining and loose, which will also help to ensure proper air circulation around the roots.
			</p>
			<p class="descriptions">
				Here is the soil mixture I use to accomplish this result, which contains roughly equal parts of the following ingredients: peat moss (with some dolomite lime), perlite, charcoal, and bark. The peat moss holds ample moisture while the dolomite lime helps adjust the pH to suitable levels. The rest of the ingredients improve drainage. The charcoal in particular absorbs odors and excess moisture while promoting beneficial bacteria.
			</p>
			<p class="descriptions">
				When watering the plant, the water should flow out through the bottom of the pot in a timely manner; the first time will be slightly slower however, due to the peat moss being dry.
			</p>
		</div>
