	<div class="row p-4 p-sm-5">
		<div class="col-md-6">
			<div class="traits">
				<h2>Planter Recommendation:</h2>
				<p class="descriptions">
					While there are numerous types of pots available, a plastic pot with plenty of drainage holes on the bottom is recommended as opposed to clay, which dries out faster and might crack. The size of the pot should be slightly larger than that of the root ball. Philodendrons generally prefer to be somewhat pot bound but also need sufficient room to grow new roots.
				</p>
				<p class="descriptions">
					Too large of a pot, however, will cause too much moisture to remain in the soil and in turn cause root rot and slow or even halt plant growth. Move the plant up to a new pot one to two inches larger than the current one when the roots have filled the pot and are tightly wrapped together.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
